Dividing testing data and training data

#randomize the order of the table
random_mushroom = mushroom_df[sample(nrow(mushroom_df)),]

#setting training data and testing data(80% training data and 20% testing data)
training_data=random_mushroom[1:6498,]
testing_data=random_mushroom[6499:8124,]

testing_vars=testing_data[,-1]

sapply(training_data,function(x) sum(is.na(x)))

Interprete the result

Based on the data above, we are able to classify 822 out of 831 “Edible” cases correctly and 704 out of 795 “poisonous” cases correctly. This means the ability of Naive Bayes algotithm to predict “Edible” cases is about 98.9% and 88.6% of “poisonous” cases resulting in an overall accuracy of 93.8%.

But the problem is the data set for our training and testing data with small size, it may have larger bias with the real-world situation.

Fourth try: neural network

library(nnet); 
library(mlbench);
#We get all the variables as input, hide layer has 3 nodes, initial random weights interval[-0.1,0.1],weight gradually decay.
nn_model=nnet(class~.,data = training_data,size=3,rang=0.1,decay=5e-4,maxit=200);

nn_predict = predict(nn_model,testing_vars)
compareTable=data.frame(true=testing_data$class,prob=nn_predict)
acc=function(comparetable){
  trueNum=0
  for (i in 1:length(comparetable[,1])){
    if (compareTable[i,1]=="e" && compareTable[i,2]<=0.5){
      trueNum=trueNum+1
    }else if (compareTable[i,1]=="p" && compareTable[i,2]>0.5){
      trueNum=trueNum+1
    }
  }
  return(trueNum/1626)
}
acc(compareTable)

Other models I have tried

  1. Logistic regression. The model shows the variables are non-related with our predicting data, which may because our variables are all factor variables so that linear regression model cannot do a lot of work here.
  2. K nearest neighbor. KNN is not help a lot in this situation (k is hard to define) since variables are all factor variables. (KNN will be very helpful, sometimes even better than SVM, if we have multi-modal classification question)
